         <entryFree xml:id="k000270" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">shengqi</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">生起</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">生起</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">shēngqǐ</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">sheng-ch`i</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000270-1"
               type="literal_translation">raising up (from center to corner) (lit.)</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-7" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000270-2"
               type="literal_translation">rise</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000270-8" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000270-3"
               type="literal_translation">grow upward</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000270</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p>under construction</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">The term shengqi, literally “rising progressively” or “growing upward” (Kroll, digital ed.), is only found in the Yingzao fashi. It refers to the gradual increase in 
                  pillar height from the central bay leveling pillars (<term ref="/keyword/k000064">pingzhu 平柱</term>) to the corner pillars (<term ref="/keyword/k000035">jiaozhu 角柱</term>). This graduated height arrangement helps maintain the structure's stability 
                  by better distributing the roof's weight. The exact measurements for the height increases are precisely regulated in the Yingzao fashi. Beyond its structural function, shengqi also 
                  contributes to the upward-curving roof corners that are a distinctive aesthetic of traditional Chinese architecture. In the Yingzao fashi, the Chinese character sheng 生 (here meaning 
                  gradual rising) is specifically chosen over the character 升 (implying direct upward movement) to emphasize this progressive elevation.</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">Research on shengqi has focused on several issues. Scholars have primarily investigated its usage patterns and applications in different types of pillars. Recent studies 
                  indicate that shengqi was used in official architecture from the <term ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang</term> to the <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming</term> dynasties (618-1644) (Liang 1983, Guo 1999). In vernacular architecture, extant examples from the Ming 
                  were discovered in Zhejiang province (Shi 2016, 39).The practice was particularly common in buildings using the chuandou <term ref="/keyword/k000011">穿鬥</term> structural system. By examining surviving buildings, 
                  researchers have found that shengqi was applied not only to eave pillars but also to inner structural pillars (Zhou and Hu, 2020). Other debates center on two aspects of measurement: 
                  some scholars analyze the proportional relationship between the height increases and the original pillar heights (Chen 1981, 17-19; Wang 2002), while others argue that craftsmen would 
                  have preferred working with whole number measurements for practical reasons (Zhang 2004, 84; Pan and He 2005, 31). Recent scholarship attempts to reconcile these two 
                  approaches (Zhang 2018, 88-89).</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">生起，作为术语仅见于《营造法式》（1103），指柱子高度從心間平柱向兩邊依次逐渐升高的做法，有助於結構的整體穩定性；《營造法式》也規定了自平柱至角柱的具體升高數值。生起不僅是結構需求，
                  也幫助塑造了中國傳統建築屋面飄逸，翼角飛揚的美學特征。“生”在《營造法式》有連續漸次變化之意，不应与升高的“升”混同。</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">学界关于生起的讨论，主要集中在它所使用的年代及適用的柱的範圍。當前研究指出，生起廣泛用於唐宋至明的官式建築（梁思成 1983，郭 1999），民間建築中至遲還存有明代浙江的案例（石 2016，39），
                  穿鬥體系中生起始終存在；實例研究也指出生起不僅用於簷柱，也可用於內柱（周和胡 2020）。一些学者进一步探討实例中的生起数值。一種思路是結合材分制度推算生起數值相對於柱子尺寸的比例值（陈明达 1981，17-19；
                  王贵祥 2002），另一種基於工匠思維傾向於取具體的整數值（张十庆 2004，84；潘和何 2005,31），近來研究有整合兩種思路的嘗試（张毅捷 2018，88-89）。</p>
            </note>
